{"cursor":"20529","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nIn mathematics, more specifically in general topology and related branches, a\n'net' or 'Moore–Smith sequence' is a generalization of the notion of a\nsequence. In essence, a sequence is a function with domain the natural numbers,\nand in the context of topology, the range of this function is usually any\ntopological space. However, in the context of topology, sequences do not fully\nencode all information about a function between topological spaces. In\nparticular, the following two conditions are not equivalent in general for a map\nf between topological spaces X and Y:\n\n#The map f is continuous #Given any point x in X, and any sequence in X\nconverging to x, the composition of f with this sequence converges to f(x)\n\nIt is true, however, that condition 1 implies condition 2 in the context of all\nspaces. The difficulty encountered when attempting to prove that condition 2\nimplies condition 1 lies in the fact that topological spaces are, in general,\nnot first-countable. If the first-countability axiom were imposed on the\ntopological spaces in question, the two above conditions would be equivalent. In\nparticular, the two conditions are equivalent for metric spaces.\n\nThe purpose of the concept of a 'net', first introduced by E. H. Moore and H. L.\nSmith in 1922, | jstor = 2370388}} is to generalize the notion of a\nsequence so as to confirm the equivalence of the conditions (with \"sequence\"\nbeing replaced by \"net\" in condition 2). In particular, rather than being\ndefined on a countable linearly ordered set, a net is defined on an arbitrary\ndirected set. In particular, this allows theorems similar to that asserting the\nequivalence of condition 1 and condition 2, to hold in the context of\ntopological spaces which do not necessarily have a countable or linearly ordered\nneighbourhood basis around a point. Therefore, while sequences do not encode\nsufficient information about functions between topological spaces, nets do\nbecause collections of open sets in topological spaces are much like directed\nsets in behaviour. The term \"net\" was coined by Kelley. Megginson, p.143\n\n'Nets' are one of the many tools used in topology to generalize certain concepts\nthat may only be general enough in the context of metric spaces. A related\nnotion, that of the filter, was developed in 1937 by Henri Cartan.\n","linknr":268,"url":"Net_(mathematics)","recorded":1362372616,"links":22,"instances":["topology","topology","mathematics","topology","mathematics","topology","mathematics"],"pdf":["http://www.math.wichita.edu/~pparker/classes/handout/netfilt.pdf"],"categories":["General topology","Articles containing proofs"],"headings":["Definition","Examples of nets","Limits of nets","Examples of limits of nets","Supplementary definitions","Examples","Properties","Cauchy nets","Relation to filters","Limit superior","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/7/8/e7827b2cc315edf7a5a2b3201ff846a0.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/f/d/0/fd0649eb8663703ecd05b99de45a5d25.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/7/8/e7827b2cc315edf7a5a2b3201ff846a0.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/7/8/e7827b2cc315edf7a5a2b3201ff846a0.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/7/8/e7827b2cc315edf7a5a2b3201ff846a0.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/9/b/89b16b1da855c10c1fa83f3a6d6370fb.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/5/0/050992bf4515002318edb223863a9ae0.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/d/b/edb24d87a18cddc7c443641a1a110118.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/7/d/57d0728b20eec70848025f88f2da25d2.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/9/b/89b16b1da855c10c1fa83f3a6d6370fb.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/c/c/bccfc7022dfb945174d9bcebad2297bb.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/3/a/d3a0327e9b5ba6ac0119e0293b28b7f0.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/5/c/05ce54404c4eb8c649e48da414f7360d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/6/0/660d7542ff754138a0a24f7e6d830a25.png","//upload.wikimedia.or